to the femoral artery","Anterior to the inguinal ligament, lateral to the femoral artery","Superior to the inguinal ligament, lateral to the femoral artery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe femoral triangle is an anatomical region located in the upper thigh. It is bounded by the inguinal ligament superiorly, the sartorius muscle laterally, and the adductor longus muscle medially. Several important structures pass through this region, including the femoral nerve, artery, and vein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct position of the femoral nerve is \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior to the inguinal ligament, lateral to the femoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E. The femoral nerve passes deep to the inguinal ligament and is located lateral to the femoral artery within the femoral triangle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior to the inguinal ligament, medial to the femoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The femoral nerve is not anterior to the inguinal ligament and is lateral, not medial, to the femoral artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior to the inguinal ligament, medial to the femoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The femoral nerve is lateral, not medial, to the femoral artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior to the inguinal ligament, lateral to the femoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The femoral nerve is not anterior to the inguinal ligament.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior to the inguinal ligament, lateral to the femoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E - The femoral nerve is inferior, not superior, to the inguinal ligament.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The femoral nerve passes deep to the inguinal ligament.","Th